The challenge. Plant biology and crop improvement are now highly data-intensive disciplines - to such a degree, in fact, that data management has become a critical challenge. Research into a crop or model species often involves generating a reference genome assembly and predicting all of the genes in the genome - which, in turn, involves isolating and sequencing the messenger RNA sequences that an organism uses as an intermediate step between the genome and the gene product. Additionally, extensive data may be collected about many other aspects of the plant's biology - for example, measurements of plant growth and production or responses to pathogens; additional sequencing to identify genetic variants among different varieties; or statistical tests to identify associations between genetic variants and characteristics of interest (such as yield or seed size or disease resistance).


The plan. We developed data management methods that are applicable across the life sciences, but we focused on one plant family in particular: the legumes. The legumes provide a useful focus because they are diverse and agriculturally important, with more than two dozen crop species; but there are sufficient evolutionary similarities to enable researchers working in one legume species to make use of information about other species in the family. The legumes are also of great interest in terms of their biology, due to a novel symbiotic association between nitrogen-fixing soil bacteria and plants in this family. This symbiosis enables use of atmospheric nitrogen by the plant, after conversion by the bacteria (in special structures in the plant's roots) into a form that the plant can utilize. Legumes play a central role in food security and nearly every cropping system worldwide. Approximately a third of all nutritional nitrogen comes from legumes, and in most developing countries, legumes are the most important source of protein. Genomic resources have been or are being developed for many legume crops, but the insular nature of these data resources limits the ability of researchers to leverage information generated in one species to infer function or identify candidate genes in another species. To address this deficiency, we propose to lay the groundwork for a federation of legume data resources to enable cross-species translational genomics.




What we did. This project developed a collection of software and methods for storing, visualizing, sharing, and analyzing genetic and genomic data across a group of related species. The project included the following main components:

Adopt and port the data currently managed in each of our custom frameworks into a set of well-integrated, open source model organism database tools;
Define data formats, metadata standards, data exchange and Web service protocols to facilitate communications between the species centric databases at various levels;
Utilize orthology, synteny, and mappings of other significant features to integrate genetic, genomic, and phenotypic data across legume species, to enable identification of common molecular bases for important traits and enable traversal across database projects;
Improve the capacity of organism database projects to collect and manage complex phenotype data, using ontologies, controlled vocabularies and well-defined protocols and schemas;
Facilitate productive data exchange by implementing a common, open, virtualized Data Repository for data exchange across sites and for stable, long-term archiving of data sets, standardized metadata, and robust methods for archiving, searching, and accessing data sets from federated genomic data portals.





The Results. To date, the project has produced eighteen peer-reviewed publications, with further papers in development. Data sets for 40 legume species, spanning the legume family, have been organized, described, made accessible in a public data repository, and incorporated into online tools for browsing, searching, and research. Two workshops held during the project brought together developers and users from the community to exchange insights into the challenges facing users and the resources under development to address their needs. Several graduate and undergraduate students, and a postdoc, were trained in bioinformatics, data management, and software development. A project website serving as a portal to resources developed in the project and by others in the community is available at legumefederation.org Sand software tools have been made available through open source repositories to assist researchers in several core areas of computational biology, including: genomic comparison and visualization, marker-trait analysis and cross-species comparison, genetic map visualization, and genomic feature visualization at full-genome scales.














